<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>JMPD's chief Superintendent  Wayne Minnaar said the department impounded the taxis for being unroadworthy.“Some of the taxis which had wires dangling on their steering wheels and with tattered chairs and everything is just falling apart,” said Minnaar.He said usually when they stop the vehicles, they take them to ther testing station and that is where it is all been tested and impounded. “With some of the taxis that were impounded on Tuesday it was no need for those vehicles to be taken for testing and they straight to the impounding JMPD offices,” he said.He said some of the taxis impounded were reported stolen and hijacked. “The so called new owners of the taxis are facing arrest as soon as they come to claim their cars back. “A total of seventeen taxis were not licensed and when checked by JMPD Number Plate Investigation Unit, one was found to have been hi-jacked in Pretoria in 2015,” said Minnaar.Commuters have praised the JMPD for putting breaks on the skorokoro taxis.Sydney Mofokeng said it was time for these taxi owners to realise that it is not all about making business but caring for commuters as well.He congratulated JMPD officers for the putting on the breaks on these taxis. "We salute you JMPD officers for putting our lives first,” he said.Minnaar said similar campaign will continue in other parts of the city.